segments.text: That's right.
How many years, how far back did that go?
Did he have that place for years?
For years.
I mean, yeah.
And there were some more of them.
They were kin somehow to the ones that owned the property for South Oakwood.
Describe Mr. Herdlicka.
Herdlicka?
Yes, sir.
Uh...
I know I couldn't do that.
I know I wouldn't know a man if I saw him again.
Only time I had any real, we always had two cows.
Either when we were on the campus or when we were in College Park, we had two cows.
And so it was my job to,
to take them and get them bred.
And the hard licker had a small Jersey bull.
So I'd have to go over there to him.
And that was quite a circus.
Did you, were the cattle, did you have those heifers here on the campus?
Those milk cows?
Yeah, we used them.
We sold the offsprings that we got, but we kept one.
Originally, when we were up on the campus, the college decided that they were going to upgrade their dairy herd.
And they had one of these big old jerseys that was
He's supposedly a 15th, 16th Jersey.
They couldn't get the papers on her, so they sold her.
Dad bought her.
He took her down there to the end of Quality Road, and we had a place for her.
Because the etymology had a whole bunch of farms in there.
a number of places we could keep cattle.
And so we kept that one and then we got an offspring off of it and that's why we got two of them.
When we came down to, when we moved down from 1924 we moved from the college to
College Park.
Now, you said 24.
You didn't mean... Yeah.
I thought you moved to College Station in 24.
Oh, okay.
I lived there five years.
When you all lived on the campus, did your mother have a maid?
No.
Did anybody help her with house cleaning?
We had...
I don't remember we, oh yeah, yeah.
You had, you could get students to come help when you were running the laundry.
You had to go outside and you had a cast iron pot with
Full of water and soap and all that stuff.
And one man that I remember was named Scott.
He later became engineers around here for a lot of things.
I think he one time or another was chief engineer for the city of Brown.
But he came down there for 25 cents an hour at 6 o'clock in the morning or
For a long time.
To help with the washing?
Yeah, they took it outside and washed the clothes.
And yeah, there were some Negroes in that particular operation.
And there were clotheslines all across the neighborhood.
They had clotheslines, yeah.
But you had to heat everything with wood.
Mm-hmm.
You had no gas.
And where did you all get the wood?
Did you buy it from?
You bought people to come.
Our contingency of wood was 15 cords of wood.
Now, a cord of wood is 10 feet long, 4 feet wide, and 4 feet high.
And you had to bring it.
They had to bring them in there.
They were cut with an axe.
And it was most all oak?
Old oak.
That's the reason we could never have a bonfire.
Sure.
The bonfire we made, we kept the crating.
Sure.
Everything in the business was shipped with crating on it.
We didn't have pasteboards like we have today.
Sure.
I'm trying to think about campus personalities.
Do you remember Coach D.X.
Bible?
Oh, yeah.
Describe him.
He was a pretty good-sized man.
Did he live on campus?
Oh, yeah.
He had a house on campus.
And his teams were good.
Was he well-liked?
He had the best there was.
And he went to the university, but that's what kind of tore it with us.
Now...
He left...
But I remember those games when they had Joel Hunt.
Yep.
He'd take that line and he'd take that line and he'd open a hole you could drive a damn car through.
Sitting up on the end where we always did it on the end of the stadiums or something, you know.
and you could see right where he was going to run.
It was pitiful.
Now, he brought young Andy Anderson with him, didn't he, as an assistant coach?
I don't know anything about that.
You remember Colonel Andy.
I know, I know, I know.
But the only occasion that I ever had with Colonel Andy was at...
When I had to take P.E.
and I couldn't run, and so he got me to take the trotter.
I trotted on the, around their track.
And I just trotted along the best I could.
When, there's Colonel Andy's son, Rusty, the doctor here.
He told me what his father had told him about the 12th man game in Dallas.
Do you remember hearing anything about it then?
Did people talk about the 12th man immediately after it happened?
No, it's something they have brought up.
They never did say too much about it.
Did you by chance know Heine Weir, the football player?
He later was dean out at Schreiner Institute in Kerrville.
He's the one whose hurt knee might have kept him from playing and why they got King Gill to come down and put his uniform on.
Oh.
Well, I don't know.
When you were a little boy, did you all go to the football games?
Yeah, we did the football games.
Matter of fact, I have some movies of a rice game in which Jaron Johnson, I got a lot of pictures of him in movies.
He'd get up on a, see, they did a
Jar and John, they'd pull him right up behind the tackle, right there.
And so when they snapped the ball, they just gave it to him.
And he would get out there and he'd say to some of the guys in front of him, I'm...
I'm coming through here.
He would tell them that, oh, some of the other guys would say, oh, John's going through here.
So that, it was just hype, you know.
But he did, it was a short change.
That's what that coach brought.
When you were a little kid, did you and your buddies go hunting or fishing?
We did fishing.
Where did you fish?
In that lake there in front of my house.
Yeah.
What we called nigger fishing.
Now, you're talking about on campus or?
No, around College Park.
College Park, uh-huh.
There was a big lake in there.
Oh, okay.
Gilchrist made us cut it open.
Because we didn't have a herd...
A permit?
A health permit.
Oh, okay.
Well, when he was built, there wasn't any health permits.
Sure.
Sure.
He was just bound to determine they were going to... Dad kept that thing full of what he called minerals.
We had a whole sewer system in there, and I had to take part in that.
I had to...
get help to do that.
Had a little bigger sand work with them.
I took care of that.
They had some down on the south end of Dexter there across the creek there.
They had that thing there and I helped lay that along the line from our house down there.
Allison was the, dad had a
A man named Allison.
He was a World War I man.
He'd been shot at.
Shot up, too.
He parachuted out and they shot him.
And he survived.
And he was around there and taught classes.
See, Dad had to reconstitute that organization there.
He had three men.
The whole department, three?
Josh Carney and one of the Whitleys.
He sold cars later.
He was there.
And another man, I don't know his name.
Who do you think would have been your dad's favorite dean of agriculture of all the people he worked with?
Dean Kyle.
Dean Kyle?
Now he served till about when?
39 he died.
So he was dean a long time.
Well, my father died in 39.
Oh, oh.
And Dean Pratt was still head of the... Dad was assistant dean.
Okay.
What were his duties as assistant dean?
Oh, he had to counsel students and
and all the time, and then you had to work on your curriculum, the ag engineering.
Where was his office as assistant dean?
I don't know.
I can't tell you that, but I do know if you go out there in the front of that white building, the administrative building, on the base of that
flagpole, you'll find his name.
Do you remember when that building was constructed?
Yes.
Describe that as much as you can.
It cost $400,000.
And that's the early 30s?
Well, you see, what happened was this.
They came along
First, let's go back a little further.
The legislature set up a building fund for these advanced colleges in there.
And originally, and they took and gave all of the, well, in case, oh, that would be your- The permanent fund?
Yeah, permanent fund.
They made a permanent fund.
But they gave them, in the case of over in East Texas, they gave them all the lumber.
And then the legislature, in all of its wisdom, decided that they wanted to change it.
So what did they do?
They took it out of East Texas, and they went out here to where this county that
over here in Texas, where it comes down to that square point, comes down here and goes to El Paso, that little county right there.
And they gave them the rights to a whole bunch of this stuff in here.
The mineral rights.
And for the lumber of it.
Okay, well, they discovered oil out there.
In its heyday,
That oil produced 37% of all the oil produced in the North American continent.
That one county.
So that's where we got the money.
We can't spend it for the permanent
bond the interest well they did that and they gave the university six million dollars well so A&M decided we ought to have part of that too so we sued them we sued them and they divided it up
two-thirds for us and one-third for us.
That's where we got the money to build all these buildings that we had over here.
And then another thing happened, I don't know how they handled that, but later on when I was teaching in 35, the state was broke.
Paid with warrants.
Because your check, if you cashed it immediately, it was discounted, wasn't it?
One and a half percent.
I got $150 a month for teaching at Tarleton.
Now, let's go back to the big administration building.
Whose idea was it to turn the campus around and extend it to the east?
Well, you built that concrete two-lane highway from the bridge all the way to Texas Avenue.
What is now Texas Avenue.
And so it was part of that?
Yes, part of that.
It came through here and this thing was all, they built that in 33 or 34.
What did, those of you living here, what did you all think about the change to the campus?
Did you all like it or not?
Oh yeah, I enjoyed it.
I enjoyed it, but it just,
The only thing I don't like about the campus is these architects and landscape people want to put humps in it.
Yeah.
They don't want you to look at anything.
When it was here, it was a flat piece of ground, and you could just travel all over the way you wanted to.
That's the only thing I would object to.
As they were building those new buildings in the early 30s, did most of those materials come on the train?
No.
No.
They came by truck.
Yeah.
You had a funny thing happen there on trucking.
The railroads
got a thing through the legislature that you couldn't haul more than a ton and a half past a depot.
If you hauled more than a ton and a half past a depot, you had to put it on the railroad right there.

and so but uh we had enough good at 30 and 34 we had enough good trucks and there were some pretty good sized ones on the market so we we could haul stuff but uh most of the gravel and the sand that came from here was taken out of
out of some places around here that no longer exist.
The one that built that highway is, you go down there beyond where the speedway is, and there's a road down in that flat there.
Well, it all came out of that right there, but it went clean to the river, I think.
There was some place back in there.
And they were trying to use, they had a bunch of Chevrolet trucks and the Ford V8 trucks.
And the Ford V8 trucks were just one out.
because you could throw that old Ford V8 in the grandma and come out of that quarter with it just loping along all the way in.
And those engines lasted.
Where the Chevrolet truck was, you had to grind it out.
And it just, you know, wide open.
And they wouldn't last.
So the Ford was the better?
The better truck that won out in that battle.
All the way from Navasota to up here.
And I remember driving a, I don't know, that was a 34 or 36 probably.
My mother said she had to go to town real quick.
She was supposed to be there a certain time.
I turned down on that thing, and we were turning 85.
And as a kid, we used to go north of Bryan, and I'd run up there many a night with kids.
We were running wide open, about 85 miles an hour, neck and neck, on a brand new piece of concrete.
With lots of fun.
You're mentioning about the sand and gravel.
Many old Aggies have mentioned about going out to the clay pits.
Now the clay pits are a different situation.
Now that was, but south and west?
No, it's off of the old Wellborn Road.
Well, it's all the road that goes into, beyond Wellborn and goes into the, you can drive it today.
goes right down there, and it turns and goes into Highway 6.
Yeah.
Yeah, you know what that is.
Yes, sir.
All right, well, there was some formations in there.
They're still there.
And they used to take the railroads and take carloads of cars, big cars, and stick them down there.
I don't know.
I think they were not.
open cars, they were closed.
But anyways, that particular stuff that was in the ground was used as a filler for some sort of a situation.
And it's known that way.
You can put a liquid through it and fill it out.
When you were a youngster, had that
Yeah, they were there.
They were already there?
And the nice thing about it was you could go swimming in it.
All right, that's what, did you ever go down, go swimming there?
I never was swimming in it.
But I've been there and looked at it.
I mean, looked at it.
And it's a real, real place to swim in.
Only place I ever saw around here was that the water would be nice and clean and slightly bluish.
stuff like that.
When you were in high school or an undergraduate here, where could and where could y'all go swimming?
Wasn't a swimming pool.
Yeah, it wasn't.
You didn't go swimming in the river, did you?
No, we didn't go swimming in that river.
That's what I... We got sick over there.
Yeah.
And the other thing,
I'll tell you why I didn't.
There was a little bit of a, before we built the lake in College Park, while I was still living up on the campus, there was a smaller lake between that and the college property.
A little small lake in there.
And a kid named Hayes who lived across the street from us, we went swimming down there.
He was a pretty good-sized kid.
And I got to meet him in my lifetime.
We'd be swimming in that thing anymore.
Did you and your buddies have dogs, cats, other pets when you lived on campus?
Oh yeah, all kinds of stuff like that.
I even had a goat.
I don't know where the

what the drill field is now the south drill field and the core area well there used to be some people in there and I don't know exactly what they were doing and they had some goats in there and one of the men had some goats and he had one of them and he couldn't feed it
So I didn't have the time to feed it.
Somehow or another it was, so he knew me and we had been talking about that goat and stuff and the goats in there.
So he brought me that thing and told me, showed me how to feed it.
He said, you can, will you do this?
And when I get ready, I'll buy it back from them.
Well, the trouble was they couldn't buy it back because it had become a pet.
It followed anybody everywhere.
Oh, really?
On the campus?
Well, all around that property.
That's what I mean.
Wherever the men were going, it went.
So I had to take it back.
I think they paid me for it.
I don't remember what happened with it.
Did you and your junior high, when you were a kid, did you and your buddies ever do any pranks, jokes?
Well, you see, one of the things is I went to A&M Consolidated School until I got through the first...
Eight or nine grades.
And those were on campus here.
They were in that old white building, what they call a music hall, I think now.
And my mother, she decided she wanted to run for the school board.
And so what happened was she ran.
And all those men down through there, all that company down through there, we don't want no woman on the school board.
We don't want no woman on the school board.
So they got all the men up.
And she lost her election.
Well, we found out, and she,
I don't know how we found out all this stuff.
I'm sure dad had a lot to do with it too.
And so they decided that they filed a state law that said if you did not have a high school in your particular district, you could transfer anywhere in Texas.
So they transferred me to Bryan.
And where was Bryan High School located then?
It was just off of 29th Street now.
It's from that big building they tore down.
Okay.
So I went to see.
No, twenty-nine.
I went thirty, thirty-one.
And about how many were in your graduating class?
Pretty good bunch.
I would imagine several hundred.
It was quite a big school.
Describe being a student at Bryan High then.
Bryan High?
What was it like?
They had what I did all the time.
They had what you call a manual training.
And they had a fellow named Smith who ran it.
And he got you in there and he was training you to build furniture.
I built one.
I've got a
Bookcase?
No.
Cedar line?
Closet?
No.
It's just a big old cedar line box with long legs.
Oh, I see.
